IMD Sounds Orange Alert For Mumbai, Thane; Red Warning For Goa | Full Forecast
Curated By :
Anushka Vats
News18.com
Last Updated:
July 24, 2025, 08:24 IST
Goa is on alert with the IMD sounding a red alert for July 24-25 and an orange alert for July 26.
Impact Shorts

An orange alert is in place for today (Representative image)

Parts of Maharashtra are set to witness heavy rain, with the India Meteorological Department (IMD) sounding an alert for several regions in western India, effective from July 24, 2025. An orange alert has been issued for Mumbai and Thane today.

For Konkan and Goa, a red alert is in place for July 24 and 25, forecasting extremely heavy rain and strong surface winds.

RECOMMENDED STORIES
Scrap Dealer Shot Dead In Bihar; Mob Blocks NH-28, Sets Accused‚Äôs House Ablaze
Priyadarshini Mattoo's Family Meets Delhi Home Minister, Strongly Objects To Killer's 'Premature Release'
Mumbai Saw Over 60% Of 2,282 Suburban Railway Deaths In 2024: Railway Ministry

The weather department has also issued an orange alert predicting heavy rain and strong winds expected for July 26.

Heavy rain with strong surface winds will continue, though at a lower intensity from July 27 to 30.

IMD Goa reported the daily rainfall recorded over a 24-hour period ending at 8:30 AM IST on July 23, 2025, at various rain gauge stations across Goa state. The highest rainfall was observed at Dabolim with 114.8 mm, followed by Mormugao at 107.2 mm, Panaji at 104.8 mm, and Ela (Old Goa) at 98.4 mm.

ADVETISEMENT

No extremely heavy rainfall (204.5 mm or more) or very heavy rainfall (115.6 to 204.4 mm) was recorded during this time. However, several stations recorded heavy rainfall between 64.5 mm and 115.5 mm.

Other stations such as Canacona, Ponda, Margao, Mapusa, Dharbandora, and Sanquelim recorded rainfall ranging from 65.6 mm to 95.8 mm. Pernem recorded moderate rainfall of 52.4 mm. No light or very light rainfall was observed at any station during this period.

Weather Forecast For Other Regions

Madhya Maharashtra is also under a red alert for the first two days (July 24-25) due to extremely heavy rain and thunderstorms with lightning and squalls. The warning decreases to orange on July 26 and 27 and further reduces to yellow from July 28 onwards.

Vidarbha faces heavy to very heavy rain and thunderstorms with squalls from July 24 to 27, with warnings easing off from July 28. No warnings are in place for July 29 and 30.

Pavan Bandari
Hans News Service | 24 July 2025 10:45 AM IST
HIGHLIGHTS
The recent monsoon season has brought beneficial rains to the Telugu states, but for the past two days, heavy downpours have been recorded in several areas.

The recent monsoon season has brought beneficial rains to the Telugu states, but for the past two days, heavy downpours have been recorded in several areas. On Tuesday, many districts in Telangana experienced significant rainfall, and Wednesday continued this pattern, with expectations of further heavy rains on Thursday.Telangana travel guide

Officials from the Hyderabad Meteorological Centre have warned that northern and central districts of Telangana are likely to face very heavy rains due to the effects of both eastern and western weather troughs. Affected areas include Adilabad, Kumuram Bheem, Mulugu, Bhadradri Kothagudem, Jayashankar Bhupalpally, and Mancherial districts, all of which are under alert.

Light to moderate rains are expected in the remaining districts, including the capital, Hyderabad.Hyderabad real estateTelangana travel guide

Officials are advising residents, especially those in low-lying areas, to remain vigilant in light of the forecasts.

Monsoon mayhem in Moga: One missing, another rescued after car submerges in overflowing drain
The locals rushed for help and pulled out the vehicle but Bawa swept away in the drain, said police
By: Express News Service
Ludhiana | July 24, 2025 01:37 IST
2 min read
Locals said that the administration failed to take any concrete steps to manage monsoon rainwater and common people were facing extreme harassment due to the rainwater (Express File/Oshwin Kadhao)

At least one man went missing and another was rescued after a car submerged in an overflowing drain in Bughipura village of Punjab‚Äôs Moga district, Wednesday, following unrelenting rainfall since Tuesday.

Inspector Harwinder Singh, SHO Mehna police station, said that one of the two occupants of the Skoda Laura car, identified as Beera, was rescued by the locals. However, another occupant Karan Bawa, in his twenties, was still missing.

‚ÄúThe state disaster response force is at the spot and rescue operations are on but he is yet to be found,‚Äù said the Inspector.

STORY CONTINUES BELOW THIS AD

Bawa and his worker Beera were travelling towards Ludhiana from Zira of Ferozepur district when their car submerged in the overflowing drain at Bughipura, said police.

The locals rushed for help and pulled out the vehicle but Bawa swept away in the drain, said police.

Manjeet Singh, sarpanch of the village said that due to unrelenting rain since Tuesday, the drains have been overflowing and the car submerged.

Bawa‚Äôs family reached the spot and urged police and administration to expedite rescue operations.

STORY CONTINUES BELOW THIS AD

Beera told local reporters that Bawa was driving the vehicle when it submerged.

‚ÄúWe were travelling towards Ludhiana when Bawa was trying to reverse the vehicle and it submerged. We had opened the doors of the vehicle and had almost come out but then he again slipped and was swept away. I kept on holding to the vehicle tightly,‚Äù said Beera.

Locals said that the administration failed to take any concrete steps to manage monsoon rainwater and common people were facing extreme harassment due to the rainwater accumulating at public places.

title: DC conducts extensive field visit to take stock of landslide, flood-prone areas - Rising Kashmir
article_text: Poonch, July 23: Deputy Commissioner Poonch, Vikas Kundal, Wednesday conducted a comprehensive visit to multiple sites across the district to inspect the current status of landslide-prone and flood-affected areas, as well as to assess the status of essential services.A statement issued here said that the Deputy Commissioner was accompanied by Chief Medical Officer, Tehsildar Haveli, Tehsildar Mandi, Xen irrigation Flood Control besides other concerned officers.During the visit, the Deputy Commissioner inspected the health care services at Primary Health Centre (PHC) Chandak and the Health Centre at Chaktroo. He reviewed the healthcare arrangements, including patient care services and the status of ongoing vaccination drives, ensuring readiness in the wake of prevailing weather-related challenges. To conduct detailed inspection of vulnerable riverbed zones, the Deputy Commissioner visited Drungali, Dingla, and adjoining areas. He assessed the flood situation and flow levels of water bodies, issuing strict instructions to the concerned Executive Engineer to maintain active monitoring of these areas. He also urged the public to refrain from venturing into riverbeds and other landslide-prone zones for their safety. Further, the Deputy Commissioner visited the Revenue Complex and the Power Station in Chandak, where he evaluated the stock position, infrastructure condition, and availability of lighting and other utilities. Emphasising preparedness, he directed all concerned departments to ensure robust arrangements, particularly in the areas of healthcare, electricity, water supply, and emergency response, during this period of heightened vulnerability due to inclement weather.
